\begin_inset Formula $s_{k}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $i_{k}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the fraction of susceptibles, infectious and recovered individuals in
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 class.
 The SIR equations for such an heterogeneous population are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\partial_{t}s_{k}=-s_{k}\sum_{l}\beta_{kl}i_{l}\\
\partial_{t}i_{k}=i_{k}\sum_{l}\beta_{kl}s_{l}-\gamma_{k}i_{k}\\
\partial_{t}r_{k}=\gamma_{k}i_{k}
\end{array}\label{eq:sir}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the conservation law 
\begin_inset Formula $1=s_{k}+i_{k}+r_{k}$
\end_inset

 (i.e., we are confined in the simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\geq0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}\geq0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}+\boldsymbol{r}\leq\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

).
 Conservation comes from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}\sum_{k}\left(s_{k}+i_{k}+r_{k}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{k}=\gamma_{k}^{-1}\partial_{t}r_{k}$
\end_inset

, the evolution of the epidemics plane follows the law 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{t}\ln s_{k}=-\sum_{l}\beta_{kl}\gamma_{l}^{-1}\partial_{t}r_{l}\label{eq:main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

i.e.
 (in vector form) 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}\ln s=-\mathcal{R}\partial_{t}r$
\end_inset

 where the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}=\textrm{diag}(\gamma)^{-1}\beta$
\end_inset

 is the basic reproduction number matrix.
 Thus, defining 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\ln s$
\end_inset

, SIR epidemics have the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y^{SIR}=\ln s_{0}-\mathcal{R}\left(r-r_{0}\right)\label{eq:straight}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

