\begin_layout Section
Vaccines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In SIR, recovered individuals are considered immune.
 Thus, a vaccination policy consists in moving a population from a point
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{s}_{0},\boldsymbol{r}_{0})$
\end_inset

 (tipically/hopefully 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}=0$
\end_inset

) to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{s}_{\Omega},\boldsymbol{r}_{\Omega})\in\Omega^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 A minimal vaccination policy is a point belonging to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Since an epidemic can have different impacts on the various classes (i.e.
 mortality rates per age classes), one can consider the advantage of having
 a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}$
\end_inset

 of recovered individuals in the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 class generated through the vaccine and not through having been infected.
 Let's assume that we start vaccination from a point 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}=(\boldsymbol{s}_{0},\boldsymbol{r}_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 This means that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{i}_{0}=\boldsymbol{1}-\boldsymbol{r}_{0}-\boldsymbol{s}_{0}$
\end_inset

 infectious individuals; let's suppose we can vaccine only sane individuals,
 i.e.
 a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{V}<\boldsymbol{s}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 if we 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

land
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on a stable point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, we will end up with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{SIR}=1-\boldsymbol{s}_{0}$
\end_inset

 recovered individuals (the 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{0}$
\end_inset

 initial ones plus the 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{i}_{0}$
\end_inset

 that were infected ) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{V}$
\end_inset

 vaccined individuals, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{\Omega}=\boldsymbol{r}_{V}+\boldsymbol{r}_{SIR}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's try a simple example: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the mortality rate in the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 class and suppose that vaccination has an irrelevant cost.
 Thus, a best policy 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{V}$
\end_inset

 would be one that optimezes the problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\min\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{r}\\
\textrm{s.t. }\boldsymbol{r}+\boldsymbol{1}-\boldsymbol{s}_{0}\in\omega
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

that, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is convex and bounded (it is the intersection of a linear constrain with
 a strictly convex surface), has a unique solution (check, this is an ansatz
 !!!).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another simple example: let's consider a vaccination policy with cost 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{V}\left(\boldsymbol{r}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The best policy would be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{V}$
\end_inset

 that minimizes the problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\min c_{V}\left(\boldsymbol{r}\right)\\
\textrm{s.t. }\boldsymbol{r}+\boldsymbol{1}-\boldsymbol{s}_{0}\in\omega
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

that is a generalization of the previous and, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is convex and bounded, would have a unique solution again if 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is monotonic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more complex optimization problem would be the case where I have a limited
 amount 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of vaccine, so that I can vaccine part of the population and let the other
 part get the infection.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d(\boldsymbol{r})$
\end_inset

 the damage to the national health system given by a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}$
\end_inset

 of the population being infected.
 Under such circumstances, the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{V}$
\end_inset

 solves the problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min c_{V}\left(\boldsymbol{r}\right)+d\left(\boldsymbol{r}_{\infty}\left(\boldsymbol{r}+\boldsymbol{r}_{0}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{\infty}\left(\boldsymbol{r}+\boldsymbol{r}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the intersection of eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:straight"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with initial conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\boldsymbol{r}_{0}+\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{s}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 to the boundary.
 Here I have relaxed the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}\in\omega$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 cannot be not obliged to belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 but surely belongs by construction to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Majorants and minorants in n dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}^{*}=\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

is the separating point between stable and unstable points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 we can associate the 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 points 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{s}_{ij}^{max}=\mathcal{R}_{ij}^{-1}\boldsymbol{1}_{j}
\]

\end_inset

; thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}_{ij}^{max}=\left(0,\ldots,0,\mathcal{R}_{ij}^{-1},0,\ldots,0\right)$
\end_inset

 has all 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 components but the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 that is (with an abuse of notation) 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ij}^{max}=\mathcal{R}_{ij}^{-1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notice that for a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}\boldsymbol{1}_{j}=\mathcal{A}_{j}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 column of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{1}_{i}^{T}\mathcal{A}\boldsymbol{1}_{j}=\mathcal{A}_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, If we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}:\mathcal{S}_{ij}=\mathcal{R}_{ij}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}_{ij}=\boldsymbol{1}_{i}^{T}\mathcal{S}\boldsymbol{1}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}_{ij}^{max}=\boldsymbol{1}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the n vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{s}_{i1}^{max},\ldots,\boldsymbol{s}_{in}^{max}\right\} $
\end_inset

 constitute an orthogonal basis in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{max}=\sum_{i}\boldsymbol{s}_{ii}^{max}$
\end_inset

; if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{ii}>1$
\end_inset

, this is interior to the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}\leq\mathbf{s}\leq\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, there are points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}>\mathbf{s}^{max}$
\end_inset

; for such points, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}\mathbf{s}>\mathcal{R}\mathbf{s}^{max}\geq\mathcal{D}\mathbf{s}^{max}=\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}_{ij}=\delta_{ij}\mathcal{R}_{ij}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the hypercube 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\boldsymbol{s}\leq\boldsymbol{s}^{max}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider the convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}=\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}\boldsymbol{s}_{ii}^{max}=diag\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\right)\mathbf{s}^{max}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}=1$
\end_inset

; such a set belongs to the hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{s}^{max}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset

, for such points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}=\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}_{ii}^{max}=\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}\boldsymbol{1}_{j}<\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the exterior of the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}:\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{s}^{max}>1$
\end_inset

.
