\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider the convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}=\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}\boldsymbol{s}_{ij}^{max}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}=1$
\end_inset

; such a set belongs to the hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{j}=1$
\end_inset

 where we have defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\theta}^{j}=\sum_{i}\boldsymbol{s}_{ij}^{max}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset

, for such points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}\right)_{j}=\left(\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}_{ij}^{max}\right)_{j}=\left(\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}\boldsymbol{1}_{j}\right)_{j}=1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
More esplicit calculation: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}\right)_{j}=\sum_{i}\alpha_{i}\sum_{k}\mathcal{R}_{ik}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{ij}^{max}\right)_{k}=\sum_{i}\alpha_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\mathcal{R}_{ik}\left(\boldsymbol{s}_{ij}^{max}\right)_{k}=\sum_{k}\mathcal{R}_{ik}\mathcal{R}_{ij}^{-1}\delta_{jk}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

; thus, this plane separate the points where the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 component of the SIR model is unstable (i.e.
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\mu}^{j}>1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}i_{j}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{j}$
\end_inset

 reaches a maximum on 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\mu}^{j}=1$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta^{j}=\left\{ \boldsymbol{s}:\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{j}\leq1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, at the intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{j}\Theta^{j}$
\end_inset

 I have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall j\left(\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}\right)_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}=\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{*}\in\bigcap_{j}\Theta^{j}$
\end_inset

; if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 is invertible, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{j}\Theta^{j}=\left\{ \boldsymbol{s}^{*}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 See fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Stability-boundaries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for an example in 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 dimensions.
 Notice that in 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 dimensions I have 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}=4$
\end_inset

 convex sets:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}<1,\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}<1$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the stable set 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}i_{1}<0,\partial_{t}i_{2}<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}>1,\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}<1$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

-unstable/
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

-stable set 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}i_{1}>0,\partial_{t}i_{2}<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}<1,\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}>1$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

-unstable/
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

-stable set 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}i_{1}<0,\partial_{t}i_{2}>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{1}>1,\boldsymbol{s}\cdot\boldsymbol{\theta}^{2}>1$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the unstable set 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}i_{1}>0,\partial_{t}i_{2}>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, there will be 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 sets corresponding to the possible stable/unstable combinations.
 
