\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}\subseteq\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 be a set of indexes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=\left\{ 1\ldots n\right\} $
\end_inset

 and let define the 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}^{\boldsymbol{k}}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{R}^{\left(\boldsymbol{k}\right)}\right]_{ij}=\begin{cases}
0 & i\in\boldsymbol{k}\vee j\in\boldsymbol{k}\\
\mathcal{R}_{ij} & \textrm{otherwhise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

; also, let also define for a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\boldsymbol{v}^{\left(\boldsymbol{k}\right)}\right]_{i}=\begin{cases}
0 & i\in\boldsymbol{k}\\
v & otherwhise
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\_^{\left(\boldsymbol{k}\right)}$
\end_inset

 sets applied to a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{i_{1}i_{2}...}$
\end_inset

 sets to zero all the components that have an index in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}$
\end_inset

.
 I can then construct the 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 vertices of the boundary of the convex polytope 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}\leq\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

by solving the 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 systems
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{R}^{\left(\boldsymbol{k}\right)}\boldsymbol{s}=\boldsymbol{1}^{\left(\boldsymbol{k}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{s}^{\boldsymbol{k}}=\left[\mathcal{R}^{\left(\boldsymbol{k}\right)}\right]^{+}\boldsymbol{1}
\]

\end_inset

where we indicate with 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{+}$
\end_inset

 the pseudo-inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that the properties of the pseudo-inverse ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{\boldsymbol{k}}=\left(\boldsymbol{s}^{\boldsymbol{k}}\right)^{(\boldsymbol{k})}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 all the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{\boldsymbol{k}}$
\end_inset

 with index in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}$
\end_inset

 are zero.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{\emptyset}=\boldsymbol{s}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{\mathcal{N}}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the linear programming problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
{\displaystyle \max}\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\boldsymbol{s}\\
s.t. & 0\leq\mathcal{R}\boldsymbol{s}\leq\boldsymbol{1}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

will have solutions on the vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{s}^{\boldsymbol{k}}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 However, in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cases I will have to choose among 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{\emptyset}$
\end_inset

 and its 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 neighbours 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{\left\{ 1\right\} },\ldots,\boldsymbol{s}^{\left\{ n\right\} }$
\end_inset

, then eventually among their 
\begin_inset Formula $n(n-1)/2$
\end_inset

 neighbours 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}^{\left\{ 1,2\right\} },\boldsymbol{s}^{\left\{ 1,3\right\} },\boldsymbol{s}^{\left\{ 1,4\right\} },\ldots,\boldsymbol{s}^{\left\{ n-1,n\right\} }$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 Remember that the vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{s}^{\boldsymbol{k}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 form a lattice where two point are adjacent if and only if their indicating
 sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k},\boldsymbol{k}'$
\end_inset

 differ by just one index.
\end_layout

